article.description: Lauren Jackson had 18 points and six rebounds, and Sue Bird scored 14 points in the Storm's 66-63 victory on Thursday.
article.headline: Seattle stars total 32 points in win
article.linkText: Jackson, Bird push Storm past Monarchs
article.story:
SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) -- The Sacramento Monarchs like an ugly
game, and Seattle's Lauren Jackson was happy to play it.

Jackson had 18 points and six rebounds, and Sue Bird scored 14
points in the Storm's 66-63 victory on Thursday.

The Monarchs focused their defensive attention on the reigning
league MVP, hacking and pushing as much as the referees allowed.
The Australian star took the punishment and still led Seattle to a
win while reaching a scoring milestone.

With a 3-pointer late in the first half, Jackson became the
youngest player to score 2,000 points in the WNBA, doing it in just
109 games.

"It kind of felt good," Jackson said. "I'll get my points
either way. ... We just hung in there with them. There wasn't much
we could do to pull away with the way it was being played."

Jackson also got into a scuffle with Yolanda Griffith under the
Seattle basket with 1:26 to play, earning technical fouls for both
stars. They smoothed things over after the game.

Jackson took just six shots, but went 9-for-11 from the free
throw line. The Monarchs' concentration on Jackson repeatedly left
Bird and her teammates open in the second half.

"This is probably the most physical team in the Western
Conference, but I think we're learning how to play better with
that," Seattle coach Anne Donovan said. "To me, that's a great
thing when other people can step up and we can still win the
game."

Sheri Sam scored eight points for the Storm, who pulled away
with a 16-5 run late in the second half for their third straight
win over Sacramento. Seattle also moved within 1½ games of Los
Angeles for the WNBA's best record.

The Monarchs made it close with Ruthie Bolton's 3-pointer and
Ticha Penicheiro's layup in the final minute, but Jackson and Betty
Lennox combined for five free throws.

Penicheiro hit a 3-pointer with 4.9 seconds left to cut
Seattle's lead to 64-63, but Bird added two more free throws.
Penicheiro missed a shot from halfcourt at the buzzer.

"They try to make it an ugly, scrambled game, and they do a
good job," Bird said. "In the second half, we did a much better
job taking care of the ball."

Bolton had a season-high 14 points for the Monarchs, whose
three-game home winning streak was snapped despite taking 21 more
shots than Seattle. Kara Lawson added 10 points, but Sacramento
went 5-for-13 from the free throw line and struggled through two
prolonged scoring droughts.

"We have to shoot better free throws if we want to win close
games like this," Bolton said.

Griffith, the Monarchs' leading scorer, was frustrated by
Seattle's defense, managing just seven points on five shots in 29
minutes.
